    "image_text_ctaeLA": {
      "type": "image_text",
      "blocks": {
        "bl_text_zMiDrj": {
          "type": "bl_text",
          "settings": {
            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h2>Tribal Influence – Inspired by North-Eastern Drapes</h2><p></p><p>When we think of sarees, our minds often go to the silks of the South, the cottons of Bengal, or the Banarasis of the North. But tucked away in the lush hills of North-East India are rich, under-celebrated traditions of textile and draping that speak of identity, resilience, and raw beauty.</p><p>Today, the first draping <strong>of our One Saree, 30 Drapes challenge</strong>, we’re drawing inspiration from <strong>tribal North-Eastern drapes</strong> — infusing the look with <strong>belted accents, shoulder wraps, and rooted strength</strong>.</p><h2>The Inspiration: North-Eastern Aesthetics</h2><p>Unlike the typical saree drape, many North-Eastern textiles like the <strong>mekhela chador (Assam)</strong>, <strong>puan (Mizoram)</strong>, and <a href=\"https://in.pinterest.com/pin/313211349104840790/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\"><strong>wrap skirts from Nagaland</strong></span></a><strong> and Manipur</strong> use shorter, layered cloths wrapped around the body. These drapes are deeply functional, climate-friendly, and culturally symbolic.</p><p>Their styling often includes:</p><ul><li><strong>Shoulder drapes</strong> that are layered or knotted<br/><br/></li><li><strong>Belted waists</strong> using fabric, leather, or beaded cords<br/><br/></li><li>Bold tribal motifs and geometric weaves<br/><br/></li><li>Minimal accessories, often replaced with handcrafted jewelry and natural fabrics</li></ul><p>Today, we’re borrowing the <strong>spirit</strong> of these drapes and adapting them to our <strong>one versatile saree</strong>.<br/><br/></p>",
