    "image_text_tLNKi3": {
      "type": "image_text",
      "blocks": {
        "bl_text_EXxjCm": {
          "type": "bl_text",
          "settings": {
            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h2>Styling Tips to Try This Look</h2><h2><br/></h2><ul><li>Choose a saree with <strong>bold stripes or geometric prints</strong> if available — to reflect tribal design.<br/><br/></li><li>Use a <strong>contrast belt</strong> — think jute, leather, or even a DIY rope tie.<br/><br/></li><li>Layer on <strong>handcrafted jewelry</strong> — especially in oxidized silver or beaded wood.<br/><br/></li><li>Keep makeup minimal but defined — think <strong>kohl eyes, earthy tones</strong>, and glowing skin.<br/><br/></li><li>Want to go bold? Add a <strong>tribal tattoo sticker</strong> on your collarbone or arm for drama.</li></ul><p></p><p></p><p></p><h2>Why This Look Matters</h2><p>This drape is not just a style statement — it’s a reminder that <strong>fashion has deep roots</strong> in indigenous cultures. North-Eastern India’s clothing traditions are fluid, gender-neutral in many ways, and prioritise <strong>function over flair</strong> — yet the aesthetic is undeniably powerful.</p><p>By paying tribute to these communities through reinterpretation, we open up conversations about inclusion, visibility, and <strong>respect for regional craftsmanship</strong>.</p><h2>Wrap Up</h2><p>The tribal-inspired drape feels fierce yet grounded. It teaches us that elegance doesn’t always come from polish — sometimes, it comes from being raw, real, and connected to the earth.</p><p>In a world of cookie-cutter fashion, today’s look is a beautiful rebellion — a reminder that the saree is not limited to any one shape, culture, or rulebook.</p><p><strong>One saree. Infinite cultures. Endless stories.</strong></p>",
